<Group view="presentation" inline-output="false" labelreference="L1791" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">a) Find the equilibrium points and study their stability.</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group></Presentation-Block><Presentation-Block>
<Group view="presentation" inline-output="false" labelreference="L1963" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group></Presentation-Block><Presentation-Block>
<Group view="presentation" inline-output="false" labelreference="L1968" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">b) Make some numerical simulations.
</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group></Presentation-Block><Presentation-Block>
<Group view="code" hide-input="false" labelreference="L1969" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">restart; with(DEtools): with(plots): with(linalg):
##### -----------------------------------------------------------
##### / x' = r_1 * x(1- x/K_1 ) -  b_1,2/K_1 * x * y
##### <Font encoding="UTF-8">\134 y' = </Font>r_2 * x(1- x/K_2 ) -  b_2,1/K_2 * x * y
##### a) Find the equilibrium points and study their stability.
##### -----------------------------------------------------------

Function1 := (x,y)-&gt;r1*x*(1-x/K1)-b12/K1*x*y;
Function2 := (x,y)-&gt;r2*y*(1-y/K2)-b21/K2*x*y;
Equation1 := diff(x(t),t) = Function1(x(t), y(t));
Equation2 := diff(y(t),t) = Function2(x(t), y(t));
Equation_System := Equation1, Equation2;

##### EQUILIBRIUM POINTS

Equilibrium_Points := solve({Function1(x,y)=0, Function2(x,y)=0}, {x,y});
JacobianSol := jacobian([Function1(x,y), Function2(x,y)], [x,y]);

Jacobian_Matrix_Point1 := subs(Equilibrium_Points[1,1], Equilibrium_Points[1,2], eval(JacobianSol));
EigenValues1 = eigenvals(Jacobian_Matrix_Point1);
##### The eigenvalues are r1 and r2. Since growth rates r1, r2 are assumed to
##### be strinctly positive, the origin is always an unstable source node

Jacobian_Matrix_Point2 := subs(Equilibrium_Points[2,1], Equilibrium_Points[2,2], eval(JacobianSol));
EigenValues2 = eigenvals(Jacobian_Matrix_Point2);
##### If <Equation executable="false" style="2D Input" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> &lt; 0, then the equilibrium point (0, K2) is a sink node and locally asymptotically stable
##### If <Equation executable="false" style="2D Input" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> &gt; 0, then the equilibrium point (0, K2) is a saddle point and unstable

Jacobian_Matrix_Point3 := subs(Equilibrium_Points[3,1], Equilibrium_Points[3,2], eval(JacobianSol));
EigenValues3 = eigenvals(Jacobian_Matrix_Point3);
##### If <Equation executable="false" style="2D Input" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> &lt; 0, then the equilibrium point (K1, 0) is a sink node and locally asymptotically stable
##### If <Equation executable="false" style="2D Input" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> &gt; 0, then the equilibrium point (K1, 0) is a saddle point and unstable

Jacobian_Matrix_Point4 := subs(Equilibrium_Points[4,1], Equilibrium_Points[4,2], eval(JacobianSol));
Jacobian_Matrix_Point4[1, 1] := factor(expand(Jacobian_Matrix_Point4[1, 1]));
Jacobian_Matrix_Point4[2, 2] := factor(expand(Jacobian_Matrix_Point4[2, 2]));
eval(Jacobian_Matrix_Point4);

EigenValues4 = eigenvals(Jacobian_Matrix_Point4);

##### Calculate the Characteristic Polynomial and set to 0
Characteristic_Equation:= charpoly(Jacobian_Matrix_Point4, lambda) = 0;

##### Clear the Denominator
##### Multiply the characteristic equation by common denominator (b12*b21 - r1*r2) to simplify the coefficients.
Simplified_Characteristic_Equation := K1*K2*(b12*b21 - r1*r2) * lhs(Characteristic_Equation) = 0;

##### Collect terms by lambda
##### collect() function organizes the equation into the form a1*lambda^2 + a2*lambda + a3 = 0
collect(Simplified_Characteristic_Equation, lambda);

##### Extract Coefficients
Coefficient1 := factor(coeff(lhs(Simplified_Characteristic_Equation), lambda, 2));
Coefficient2 := factor(coeff(lhs(Simplified_Characteristic_Equation), lambda, 1));
Coefficient3 := factor(coeff(lhs(Simplified_Characteristic_Equation), lambda, 0));
##### The necessary and sufficient condition for stability is to have Re(lambda) &lt; 0 (Real part of lambda &lt; 0). ##### This is true if the coefficients of the characteristic equation have the same sign (Routh-Hurwitz). For the characteristic equation before simplification the coefficients are 1, Coefficient2/Coefficient1 and Coefficient3/Coefficient1. That means Coefficient2/Coefficient1 &lt; 0 and Coefficient3/Coefficient1 &gt; 0.
##### If <Equation executable="true" style="2D Input" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> &lt; 0, then Coefficient1 &lt; 0. If Coefficient2 &gt; 0 and Coefficient3 &lt; 0 the equilibrium point <Equation executable="false" style="2D Input" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> is locally asymptotically stable, otherwise unstable.
##### If <Equation executable="true" style="2D Input" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> &gt; 0, then Coefficient1 &gt; 0. If Coefficient2 &lt; 0 and Coefficient3 &gt; 0 the equilibrium point <Equation executable="false" style="2D Input" input-equation="" display=""></Equation> is locally asymptotically stable, otherwise unstable.</Text-field>
</Input>
